{"title_page": "Commanders of World War II", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{TopicTOC-World War II}}\n{{WWII timelines}}\n\nThe '''Commanders of World War II''' were for the most part career [[Officer (armed forces)|officers]]. They were forced to adapt to new technologies and forged the direction of modern warfare. Some political leaders, particularly those of the principal dictatorships involved in the conflict, [[Joseph Stalin]] (Soviet Union), [[Adolf Hitler]] (Germany), [[Benito Mussolini]] (Italy) and Emperor [[Hirohito]] (Japan), acted as supreme military commanders as well as dictators for their respective countries or empires.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\">{{cite book|author1=I.C.B Dear|author2=M.R.D. Foot|title=Oxford Companion to the Second World War|edition=paperback|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=978-0-19-280666-6}}</ref>\n\n== Military commanders ==\n\n=== Allied Forces ===\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000; color:white;\"| Armed Force\n! colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! Highest Rank\n! Highest Award\n! Fate\n! Theatres / Battles\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" rowspan=\"12\"|'''Army'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Alan Brooke, 1st Viscount Alanbrooke|Alan Brooke]]\n| [[File:1st Viscount Alanbrooke 1947.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Field Marshal]]\n| [[Knight of the Garter]].\n| Served as [[Chief of the Imperial General Staff|CIGS]].\n|\n* [[Chief of the Imperial General Staff]]\n* [[Battle of the Ypres-Comines Canal]]\n* [[Operation Ariel]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commanded the II corps of the British Expeditionary Force at the Battle of France. Later served as the [[Chief of the Imperial General Staff]].<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bernard Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery of Alamein|Bernard Montgomery]]\n| [[File:Bernard Law Montgomery.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Field Marshal]]\n| [[Knight of the Garter]].\n| Served as [[Chief of the Imperial General Staff|CIGS]], and deputy leader of [[NATO]].\n|\n* [[Western Desert Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Alam el Halfa]]\n* [[Second Battle of El Alamein]]\n* [[Battle of El Agheila]]\n* [[Tunisia Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Medenine]]\n* [[Operation Pugilist]]\n* [[Battle of Wadi Akarit]]\n* [[Operation Husky]]\n* [[Operation Avalanche]]\n* [[Western Front (World War II)]]\n* [[Operation Overlord]]\n* [[Battle for Caen]]\n* [[Operation Epsom]]\n* [[Operation Goodwood]]\n* [[Operation Cobra]]\n* [[Falaise pocket]]\n* [[Operation Market Garden]]\n* [[Battle of the Bulge]]\n* [[Western Allied invasion of Germany]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| A veteran of [[World War I]] and the [[Irish War of Independence]], Great General of the [[British Army]], entered the Second World War as a divisional commander within the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]], defending France and then took command of [[II Corps (United Kingdom)|II Corps]] during the [[evacuation at Dunkirk]]. After several Corps appointments was placed in command of South-Eastern Command before being dispatched to Egypt to take command of the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]], following the death of [[William Gott]]. Won the [[Second Battle of El Alamein]] and played a crucial role in the completion of the [[North African Campaign]]. Then led the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]] during the [[Allied invasion of Sicily|Battle of Sicily]] and then the [[Allied invasion of Italy|invasion of Italy]] itself. Was transferred back to the United Kingdom to take command of the [[21st Army Group]] and led all Allied ground forces during [[Operation Overlord]]. Following the conclusion of this campaign, relinquishing the role of Ground Forces commander, he continued to lead [[21st Army Group]] throughout the rest of the 1944-1945 [[North West Europe Campaign]].<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" /><ref name=\"NT5Y\">{{cite book|author=Lord Ismay|title=NATO, the first 5 years|publisher=NATO archives|year=2001|url=http://www.nato.int/archives/1st5years/annexes/c4.htm}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Harold Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Tunis|Harold Alexander]]\n| [[File:HarolAlexanderD 026065.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Field Marshal]]\n| [[Order of the Bath|Knight Grand Cross of the Most Honourable Order of the Bath]]\n| Governor General of Canada.\n|\n* [[Battle of Dunkirk]]\n* [[Mediterranean and Middle East Theatre]]\n* [[Adriatic Campaign of World War II]]\n* [[North African Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Tunisia]]\n* [[Italian Campaign (World War II)]]\n|- style=\"background:white;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|The last British soldier to evacuate Dunkirk, replaced Auchinleck from command at North Africa, and turned the tide in the Allies' favour. Defeated the Germans in North Africa. Staged a successful invasion of Italy, and as Commander-in-Chief of Allied Forces liberated it in 1944 before becoming Supreme Commander of the Allied Forces Headquarters, responsible for all military operations in the Mediterranean Theatre.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Archibald Wavell, 1st Earl Wavell|Archibald Wavell]]\n| [[File:Archibald Wavell2.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Field Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n| [[Viceroy of India]], returned to England in 1947 and became [[High Steward of Colchester]].\n|\n* [[Mediterranean and Middle East Theatre]]\n* [[Adriatic Campaign of World War II]]\n* [[North African campaign]]\n* [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]]\n* [[Anglo-Iraqi War]]\n* [[Syria\u2013Lebanon Campaign]]\n* [[Burma Campaign 1942\u201343]]\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commander-in-Chief of British Forces in the Middle East 1939\u20131941. Commander-in-Chief in India 1941\u20131942. Commander of ABDACOM 1942. Commander-in-Chief in India 1942\u20131943. Viceroy of India 1943-1947.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[John Vereker, 6th Viscount Gort|Viscount Gort]]\n| [[File:Lord Gort and Lieutenant General Pownall cropped.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Field Marshal]]\n| Holder of the [[Victoria Cross]].\n| Died in 1946.\n|\n* [[Western Front (World War II)]]\n* [[Battle of France]]\n* [[Battle of Dunkirk]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|A World War I hero, he played a major role in mobilising and arming the British forces during the [[Phony War]]. He took command of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] for the German invasion of France, and despite courageous fighting, was overwhelmed by German military tactics. When his troops were trapped in Dunkirk, he disobeyed orders from French and British command to attack and decided to evacuate, a decision which saved the lives of over 300,000 soldiers.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Claude Auchinleck]]\n| [[File:Auchinleck (cropped).jpg|100px]]\n| [[General (United Kingdom)|General]]\n| [[Order of the Bath]]\n| [[Commander-in-Chief, India]]\n|\n* [[Mediterranean and Middle East theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Adriatic Campaign of World War II]]\n* [[North African Campaign]]\n* [[Anglo-Iraqi War]]\n* [[Operation Crusader]]\n* [[Battle of Gazala]]\n* [[First Battle of El Alamein]]\n|- style=\"background:white;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Organised the Home Guard to protect against [[Operation Sea Lion]]. A quick response to the Iraq revolt impressed Churchill, who appointed him Commander-in-Chief of the North Africa forces. Frequent disagreements with British command, coupled with significant loss of territory against Rommel, forced him to be reassigned back to India. He fared better in this theatre, successfully mobilising Indian forces against the Burma invasion.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#3c4645; color:white;\" rowspan=\"6\"|'''Air Force'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Charles Portal, 1st Viscount Portal of Hungerford|Charles Portal]]\n| [[File:MRAF Sir Charles Portal.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of the Royal Air Force]]\n| [[Knight of the Garter]]\n| Chairman of British Aircraft Corporation.<ref name=\"rafweb1\">[http://www.rafweb.org/Biographies/Portal.htm C A Portal_P]</ref>\n|\n* [[Chief of the Air Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of Air Staff]]\n* [[Adlertag]]\n* [[Strategic bombing during World War II]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Strong advocate of area bombing. Took over as head of the RAF after the [[Battle of Britain]]. Continually launched air raids against Germany, especially targeting civilian populations.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Sir Arthur Harris, 1st Baronet|Arthur Harris]]\n| [[File:Air Chief Marshal Sir Arthur Harris.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Air Chief Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Manager of the South African Marine Corporation\n|\n* [[Strategic bombing during World War II]]\n* [[Combined Bomber Offensive]]\n* [[Pointblank directive]]\n* [[Battle of the Ruhr]]\n* [[Bombing of Kassel in World War II]]\n* [[Battle of Berlin (RAF campaign)]]\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Assisted [[Charles Portal]] in the strategic bombing campaign against Germany.\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Hugh Dowding, 1st Baron Dowding|Hugh Dowding]]\n| [[File:Hugh Dowding.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Air Chief Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Dismissed as head of fighter command in November 1940. Became a [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophist]] after the war. Died in February 1970, aged 87 and buried in [[Westminster Abbey]].\n|\n* [[Battle of Britain]]\n|- style=\"background:white;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Leader in World War I of an RFC Squadron. Commander of the [[Battle of Britain]]. Deservedly credited with saving Britain from defeat.\n|- style=\"background:white;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:navy; color:white;\" rowspan=\"6\"|'''Navy'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Andrew Cunningham, 1st Viscount Cunningham of Hyndhope|Andrew Cunningham]]\n| [[File:Andrew Cunningham cropped.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n| [[Knight of the Thistle]]\n| Served as [[Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland]]. Died in June 1963, buried at sea off [[Portsmouth]].\n|\n* [[French West Africa in World War II]]\n* [[Battle of the Mediterranean]]\n* [[Battle of Calabria]]\n* [[Battle of Taranto]]\n* [[Battle of Cape Matapan]]\n* [[Siege of Malta (World War II)]]\n* [[Operation Torch]]\n* [[Operation Retribution (1943)]]\n* [[Operation Husky]]\n|- style=\"background:#ffffff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| [[First Sea Lord]] 1943-1946.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Louis Mountbatten]]\n| [[File:Admiral Lord Louis Mountbatten, 1943. TR1230 (cropped).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n| [[Knight of the Garter]]\n| [[Viceroy of India]] until 1947. First Sea Lord from 1954 to 1957.\n|\n* [[Battle of Dieppe]]\n* [[South-East Asian theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Burma Campaign]]\n* [[Operation Tiderace]]\n|- style=\"background:white;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Supreme Allied Commander of [[South East Asia Command|SEAC]]. Under him were such famous generals as [[William Slim]] and [[Joseph Stilwell]].<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Dudley Pound|Sir Alfred Pound]]\n| [[File:SirDudleyPound.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n| [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Died of illness, October 1943.\n|\n* [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n|- style=\"background:white;vertical-align: top;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| [[First Sea Lord]] 1939-1943.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|}\n\n[[James Somerville]]\n\n==== France ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000; color:white;\"| Armed Force\n! colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! Highest Rank\n! Highest Award\n! Fate\n! Theatres / Battles\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" rowspan=\"10\"|'''Army'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Charles de Gaulle]]\n| [[File:De Gaulle-OWI.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Army General (France)|G\u00e9n\u00e9ral de Brigade]]\n| [[Legion of Honor|Grand Master Legion of Honor]]\n| Took control of France as President and was instrumental in creating the Fifth French Republic.\n|\n* [[Battle of France]]\n* [[Battle of Montcornet]]\n* [[Battle of Abbeville]]\n* [[West Africa Campaign (World War II)|West African Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Dakar]]\n* [[Battle of Gabon]]\n* [[Free French Forces]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Defied [[Vichy France]] by vowing to continue fighting after the French surrender. He headed with de Tassigny the [[Free French Forces]], who assisted the Allies in the [[liberation of France]] in 1944.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Jean de Lattre de Tassigny]]\n| [[File:De Lattre.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of France]]\n| [[Legion of Honor|Grand Master Legion of Honor]]\n| Later commanded French troops in the [[First Indochina War]].\n|\n* [[Invasion of Elba]]\n* [[Operation Dragoon]]\n* [[Colmar Pocket]]\n* [[French Resistance]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Defied [[Vichy France]] by vowing to continue fighting after the French surrender. He headed with Charles de Gaulle the [[Free French Forces]], who assisted the Allies in the [[liberation of France]] in 1944.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Alphonse Juin]]\n| [[File:GenJuin.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of France]]\n| [[Legion of Honor|Grand Cross Legion of Honor]]\n| Became [[Resident (title)|Resident General]] in [[Morocco]].\n|\n* [[Winter Line]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commander of the Vichy French forces in North Africa until 1942, then commander of the [[French Expeditionary Corps (1943\u20131944)|French Expeditionary Corps]] in Tunisia and Italy.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Maurice Gamelin]]\n| [[File:Gamelin.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Army General (France)|G\u00e9n\u00e9ral d'Arm\u00e9e]]\n| [[Legion of Honor|Grand Cross Legion of Honor]]\n| Died in 1958.\n|\n* [[Saar Offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Belgium]]\n* [[Battle of France]]\n* [[Battle of Sedan (1940)]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commander-in-Chief of French army during Battle of France, was replaced on 20 May 1940.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Maxime Weygand]]\n| [[File:Time Maxime Weygand 10 30 33 cropped.jpg|100px]]\n| [[G\u00e9n\u00e9ral d'arm\u00e9e]]\n| [[Legion of Honor|Grand Cross Legion of Honor]]\n| Arrested on charges of treason but acquitted.\n|\n* [[Battle of Belgium]]\n* [[Battle of France]]\n* [[Battle of Abbeville]]\n* [[Battle of Dunkirk]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commander-in-Chief of French army during the Battle of France from 20 May 1940 until the surrender of France. Oversaw the creation of the Weygand line, an early application of the [[Hedgehog tactic]].<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:navy; color:white;\" rowspan=\"2\"|'''French Navy'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Fran\u00e7ois Darlan]]\n| [[File:Fran\u00e7ois Darlan.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Admiral of the Fleet]]\n| [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|War Cross]]\n| Murdered by Bonnier de La Chapelle December 1942.\n|\n* [[North African Campaign]]\n* [[Attack on Mers-el-K\u00e9bir|Mers-el-K\u00e9bir]]\n* [[Operation Torch]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Built up the French Navy to prepare for war, only to see it destroyed by the British Navy. Served the Vichy France government and was tipped to become P\u00e9tain's successor. Was commander of [[Vichy French]] forces in [[Operation Torch]]. After arranging a ceasefire, he defected to the Allied side.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|}\n\n==== United States ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000; color:white;\"| Armed Force\n! colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! Highest Rank\n! Highest Award\n! Fate\n! Theatres / Battles\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" rowspan=\"12\"|'''Army'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[George Marshall]]\n| [[File:George Catlett Marshall, general of the US army.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]]\n| [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]], [[Silver Star]]\n| As Secretary of State his name was given to the [[Marshall Plan]], for which he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1953.\n|\n* [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Was the aide to General [[John J. Pershing|Pershing]] after World War I. Was Chief of Staff having overall command of the US Army during and before World War II. Marshall served as the U.S. Army Chief of Staff during the war and as the chief military adviser to President Franklin D. Roosevelt. Many of the American generals that were given top commands during the war were either picked or recommended by Marshall, including [[Dwight Eisenhower]], [[Lloyd Fredendall]], [[Lesley J. McNair]], [[Mark W. Clark]] and [[Omar Bradley]].<ref>Ossad, Steven L., ''Command Failures: Lessons Learned from Lloyd R. Fredendall'', Army Magazine, March 2003</ref> He led the rapid growth of US forces, co-ordinated the Western Allies and promoted postwar reconstruction of Europe.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]\n| [[File:General Dwight D. Eisenhower, Supreme Allied Commander, at his headquarters in the European theater of operations. He... - NARA - 520686.tif|100px]]\n| [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]]\n| [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]], [[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Navy)|Navy Distinguished Service Medal]].\n| After liberating Europe, served as NATO head and president of Columbia University before being elected the 34th [[President of the United States]].\n|\n* [[Mediterranean and Middle East theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Adriatic Campaign of World War II]]\n* [[North African Campaign]]\n* [[Italian Campaign (World War II)]]\n* [[Western Front (World War II)]]\n* [[Western Allied invasion of Germany]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| In December 1943, President Roosevelt decided that Eisenhower\u2014not Marshall\u2014would be [[Supreme Allied Commander]] in [[Europe]]. The following month, he resumed command of [[European Theater of Operations United States Army]] (ETOUSA) and the following month was officially designated as the [[Supreme Allied Commander]] of the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe]] (SHAPE), serving in a dual role until the end of hostilities in Europe in May 1945. He was charged in these positions with planning and carrying out the Allied assault on the coast of Normandy in June 1944 under the code name [[Operation Overlord]], to head the liberation of Europe on the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]] and the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany|invasion of Germany]].\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Douglas MacArthur]]\n| [[File:Douglas MacArthur 58-61.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]]\n| [[Medal of Honor]], [[Armed Forces of the Philippines Medal of Valor|Philippine Medal of Valor]]\n| Tasked with rebuilding Japan after the war. Later involved in the [[Korean War]].\n|\n* [[South West Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Philippines Campaign (1941\u201342)]]\n* [[Solomon Islands campaign]]\n* [[New Guinea campaign]]\n* [[Salamaua\u2013Lae campaign]]\n* [[Admiralty Islands campaign]]\n* [[Philippines Campaign (1944\u201345)]]\n* [[Borneo campaign (1945)]]\n* [[Japan campaign]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Recalled from retirement prior to the start of the Pacific war. Early on in World War II, received the [[Medal of Honor]] for extreme bravery. Was disappointed to relinquish the Philippines to the Japanese. Promising to return, he did so in 1945 and whilst in Manila, prepared for war in [[Operation Downfall|Japan itself]]. MacArthur presided over the [[Japanese Unconditional Surrender]] in 1945. His strategy of maneuver, air strikes and force avoidance meant that soldiers under his command faced relatively low casualties.\n<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Omar Bradley]]\n| [[File:Omar Bradley.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]]\n| [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]] (Army and Navy).\n| Promoted to General of the Army during the [[Korean War]] (after serving in the rank of General during World War II). Became Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff\n|\n* [[Battle of Hill 609]]\n* [[Western Front (World War II)]]\n* [[Operation Cobra]]\n* [[Operation L\u00fcttich]]\n* [[Falaise pocket]]\n* [[Allied advance from Paris to the Rhine]]\n* [[Battle of H\u00fcrtgen Forest]]\n* [[Operation Queen]]\n* [[Battle of the Bulge]]\n* [[Western Allied invasion of Germany]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| This former infantry school instructor entered the war under Patton, later becoming his boss. Towards the end of the war, led a force of over 1.3 million troops (America's largest to serve under one man).<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Mark W. Clark]]\n| [[File:Mark Wayne Clark 1943.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]] (Army and Navy).\n| Became head of the Citadel\n|\n* [[Allied invasion of Italy]]\n* [[Bernhardt Line]]\n* [[Battle of San Pietro Infine]]\n* [[Battle of Monte Cassino]]\n* [[Operation Shingle]]\n* [[Battle of Cisterna]]\n* [[Gothic Line]]\n* [[Spring 1945 offensive in Italy|Operation Grapeshot]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Led the triumphal entry into Rome. Served under General [[Harold Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Tunis|Harold Alexander]]. Ordered the destruction of the religious abbey at [[Monte Cassino]]. Was [[commander-in-chief]] in Italy from late 1944.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[George S. Patton|George S. Patton, Jr.]]\n| [[File:Luxembourg - General Patton (12744889054).jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]\n| Died in a road accident 4 months after the end of the war.\n|\n* [[Operation Torch]]\n* [[Battle of El Guettar]]\n* [[Operation Vulcan]]\n* [[Battle of Sicily]]\n* [[Battle of Chambois]]\n* [[Falaise pocket]]\n* [[Battle of Fort Driant]]\n* [[Battle of Metz]]\n* [[Battle of the Bulge]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| An aggressive general whose ferocious military thrusts earned him admiration and respect from all participants in the war (and at times endangered his military career). Successfully used the German tactic of armored [[blitzkrieg]] against the Germans.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:navy; color:white;\" rowspan=\"10\"|'''Navy'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ernest King]]\n| [[File:80-G-302273 (26222660441).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Fleet admiral (United States)|Fleet Admiral]]\n| [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]\n| Retired on December 15, 1945.\n|\n* [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/> United States [[Chief of Naval Operations]].\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Chester W. Nimitz]]\n| [[File:Chester Nimitz-fleet-admiral.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Fleet admiral (United States)|Fleet Admiral]]\n| [[Legion of Honour]], [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]\n| Served as Chief of Naval Operations.\n|\n* [[Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Battle of Midway]]\n* [[Solomon Islands campaign]]\n* [[Philippines Campaign (1944\u201345)]]\n* [[Gilbert and Marshall Islands campaign]]\n* [[Mariana and Palau Islands campaign]]\n* [[Volcano and Ryukyu Islands campaign]]\n* [[Japan campaign]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| After the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]], took command of the Pacific Ocean areas, and turned around USA's fortunes in the [[Battle of Midway]]. Closed the war with operations in the Leyte Gulf and Okinawa.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[William Halsey, Jr.]]\n| [[File:Admiral William F. Halsey.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Fleet admiral (United States)|Fleet Admiral]]\n| [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]\n| Retired 1947.\n|\n* [[Marshalls\u2013Gilberts raids]]\n* [[Solomon Islands Campaign]]\n* [[Guadalcanal campaign]]\n* [[New Georgia Campaign]]\n* [[Philippines Campaign (1944\u201345)]]\n* [[Bombing of Kure (July 1945)]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Commander of [[Pacific Ocean Areas (command)|South Pacific Area]] 1942-1944. Commander of [[United States Third Fleet]] 1944-1945.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/faqs/faq36-5.htm|accessdate=2007-01-03|title=Fleet Admiral Halsey Jr Profile at Naval Historical center}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Frank Jack Fletcher]]\n| [[File:Fletcher-cropped.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Admiral]]\n| [[Medal of Honor]]\n| Chairman of the General Board, retired in 1947.\n|\n* [[Marshalls\u2013Gilberts raids]]\n* [[Battle of Coral Sea]]\n* [[Battle of Midway]]\n* [[Solomon Islands Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of the Eastern Solomons]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|\nRecipient of the [[Medal of Honor]] for saving hundreds of refugees during the United States occupation of Veracruz in April 1914 during the [[Mexican Revolution]]. Operational commander at the pivotal Battles of Coral Sea and of Midway; nephew of Admiral Frank Friday Fletcher. In November 1942, he became Commander, Thirteenth Naval District and Commander, Northwestern Sea Frontier. A year later, he was placed in charge of the Northern Pacific area <sup>[according to Oxford companion to second world war, this occurred in October 1942]</sup>.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Raymond A. Spruance]]\n| [[File:Ray Spruance.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Admiral]]\n| [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]\n| Served as [[President of the Naval War College]].\n|\n* [[Battle of Midway]]\n* [[Solomon Islands Campaign]]\n* [[Mariana and Palau Islands campaign]]\n* [[Volcano and Ryukyu Islands campaign]]\n* [[Japan campaign]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Commander of two of the most significant battles of the war, [[Battle of Midway]] and the [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]].\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#3c4645; color:white;\" rowspan=\"6\"|'''USAAF'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Henry H. Arnold|Henry Arnold]]\n| [[File:021002-O-9999G-013.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General of the Air Force]]\n| [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]\n| &nbsp;\n|\n* [[Chief of Staff of the United States Air Force]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Member of the US Joint Chiefs of Staff, and the Combined Chiefs of Staff committees.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ira C. Eaker]]\n| [[File:LTG Ira Eaker.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]] (Army, Navy and Air Force)\n| Became deputy commander of the Army Air Forces until retirement in 1947.\n|\n* [[Interception of the Rex]]\n* [[Operation Cockade]]\n* [[Defence of the Reich|Strategic bombing campaign]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Commander of the 8th US Bomber command.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Carl Andrew Spaatz|Carl Spaatz]]\n| [[File:Carl Spaatz.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Air Force Cross (United States)|Air Force Cross]]\n| Replaced Arnold in September 1947 to become chief of the US Air Force.\n|\n* [[Operation Flax]]\n* [[Strategic bombing during World War II]]\n* [[Combined Bomber Offensive]]\n* [[Pointblank directive]]\n* [[Bombing of Kassel in World War II]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| One of the pioneers of US military aviation, Spaatz advocated the use of scientific analysis to bombing raids, and made effective use of long range fighters, tactics which helped the Allies achieve air superiority over Europe.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|}\n\n[[Husband E. Kimmel]]<br/>\n[[Walter Short]]\n\n==== Soviet Union ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000; color:white;\"| Armed Force\n! colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! Highest Rank\n! Highest Award\n! Fate\n! Theatres / Battles\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" rowspan=\"16\"|'''Army'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Georgy Zhukov]]\n| [[File:Zhukov-LIFE-1944-1945.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of the Soviet Union]]\n| Twice an [[Order of Victory]], four times [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]\n| Became Soviet member of the Allied Control Council for Germany, Minister of Defense of the Soviet Union 1955-57\n|\n* [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n* [[Operation Barbarossa]]\n* [[Siege of Leningrad]]\n* [[Battle of Moscow]]\n* [[Battles of Rzhev]]\n* [[Operation Mars]]\n* [[Case Blue]]\n* [[Battle of Stalingrad]]\n* [[Battle of Kursk]]\n* [[Dnieper\u2013Carpathian Offensive]]\n* [[Kamenets-Podolsky pocket]]\n* [[Operation Bagration]]\n* [[Vistula\u2013Oder Offensive]]\n* [[Operation Solstice]]\n* [[Battle of Berlin]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Involved in nearly every major battle on the Eastern Front. He successfully led the defense of Moscow and later relieved Leningrad. After vying with Rokossovsky for overall command, he led all Soviet armies in the closing stages of the war and at the Battle for Berlin.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Aleksandr Vasilevsky]]\n| [[File:Aleksandr Vasilevsky 4.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of the Soviet Union]]\n| Twice an [[Order of Victory]], twice [[Hero of the Soviet Union]].\n| Soviet Defence Minister\n|\n* [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n* [[Operation Barbarossa]]\n* [[Battle of Moscow]]\n* [[Second Battle of Kharkov]]\n* [[Case Blue]]\n* [[Battle of Stalingrad]]\n* [[Operation Bagration]]\n* [[East Prussian Offensive]]\n* [[Manchurian Strategic Offensive Operation]]\n* [[Soviet\u2013Japanese War]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Stalin's strategic specialist who planned and carried through many successful Soviet operations as overall commander, particularly the encirclement at Stalingrad and the grand plan for Bagration. Commander-in-Chief of Soviet Forces in the Far East during Manchurian Strategic Offensive Operation.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Konstantin Rokossovsky]]\n| [[File:Konstanty Rokossowski, 1945.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of the Soviet Union]], [[Marshal of Poland]]\n| [[Order of Victory]], twice [[Hero of the Soviet Union]].\n| Polish Defense Minister\n|\n* [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n* [[Case Blue]]\n* [[Battle of Stalingrad]]\n* [[Third Battle of Kharkov]]\n* [[Battle of Kursk]]\n* [[Battle of Dnieper]]\n* [[Dnieper\u2013Carpathian Offensive]]\n* [[Operation Bagration]]\n* [[East Prussian Offensive]]\n* [[East Pomeranian Offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Berlin]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Decisive role in the Battle for Moscow, led encirclement forces at Stalingrad, broke German counter-attack at Kursk, advanced into Poland and eventually linked up with the Americans at [[Wismar]].<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Boris Shaposhnikov]]\n| [[File:B Shaposhnikov02.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of the Soviet Union]]\n| Three [[Orders of Lenin]]\n| Commandant of the Voroshilov Military Academy. Died in 1945.\n|\n* [[Mozg Armii|Pre-emptive war]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Chief of the General Staff 1937-1940, 1941-1942. Organized pre-war buildup of the [[Red Army]].\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ivan Bagramyan]]\n| [[File:\u0411\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u044f\u043d \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0425\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of the Soviet Union]]\n| Twice [[Hero of the Soviet Union]].\n| Soviet Army commander\n|\n* [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n* [[Operation Barbarossa]]\n* [[Battle of Rostov (1941)|Battle of Rostov]]\n* [[Battle of Moscow]]\n* [[Second Battle of Kharkov]]\n* [[Battle of Kursk]]\n* [[Siege of Leningrad]]\n* [[Operation Bagration]]\n* [[Baltic Offensive]]\n* [[East Prussian Offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Memel]]\n* [[Battle of K\u00f6nigsberg]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Bagramyan's experience in military planning as a chief of staff allowed him to distinguish himself as a capable commander in the early stages of the Soviet counter-offensives against Nazi Germany.\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Nikolai Fyodorovich Vatutin|Nikolai Vatutin]]\n|\n| [[General of the Army (USSR)|General of the Army]]\n| [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]\n| Killed by the [[Ukrainian Insurgent Army]].\n|\n* [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n* [[Battle of Stalingrad]]\n* [[Third Battle of Kharkov]]\n* [[Battle of Kursk]]\n* [[Battle of Kiev (1943)]]\n* [[Dnieper\u2013Carpathian Offensive]]\n* [[Kamenets-Podolsky pocket]]\n* [[Korsun-Cherkassy Pocket]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Deputy of the Chief of the General Staff of the Red Army. Played a decisive role at Kursk, outmanoeuvered German commander Manstein and later routed German forces in Korsun salient.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>{{Additional citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ivan Konev]]\n| [[File:Ivan Konev 1945.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of the Soviet Union]]\n| [[Order of Victory]], Twice [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]\n| Appointed head of the Soviet forces in East Germany. Served as chief of the Soviet Armed Forces and Warsaw Pact.\n|\n* [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n* [[Battles of Rzhev]]\n* [[Battle of Kursk]]\n* [[Battle of the Dnieper]]\n* [[Battle of Kiev (1943)]]\n* [[Dnieper\u2013Carpathian Offensive]]\n* [[Kamenets-Podolsky pocket]]\n* [[Uman\u2013Boto\u015fani Offensive]]\n* [[First Jassy\u2013Kishinev Offensive]]\n* [[Lvov\u2013Sandomierz Offensive]]\