align: top;\"\n| rowspan=10 style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" |'''Army'''\n| rowspan=2| [[Vernon Sturdee]]\n|[[File:Vernon Sturdee 093811.JPG|100px]]\n|[[Lieutenant General]]\n|[[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n|\n* Sturdee served as the Chief of General Staff and commanded the First Australian Army (1939-1945). \n* On 6 September 1945 he was the senior Allied officer present at the surrender of Japanese Forces in Rabaul in the South West Pacific theatre.\n* On 1 December 1945 Sturdee was appointed Commander in Chief of the Australian Military Forces, overseeing the demobilisation of the wartime army. He was mentioned in despatches for a third time on 6 March 1947.\n|Chief of General Staff and then Commander in Chief\n|-\n| colspan=6| \n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Brudenell White]]\n| [[File:Brudenell White (AWM 001110).jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Killed in the [[Canberra air disaster, 1940]].\n|\n* [[Chief of the General Staff (Australia)|Chief of the General Staff]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|[[Chief of Army (Australia)|Chief of the General Staff]] (March\u2013August 1940)\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Thomas Blamey]]\n| [[File:Blamey.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]]\n| Promoted to [[Field Marshal]] in 1950. Became an author and promoted welfare of ex-servicemen.\n|\n* [[Mediterranean and Middle East theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Battle of Greece]]\n* [[South West Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n* [[New Guinea campaign]]\n* [[Kokoda Track campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Wau]]\n* [[Landing at Nadzab]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commander-in-chief of Australian Armed Forces and commander-in-chief of Allied Land Forces in the [[South West Pacific Area]].\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Edmund Herring]]\n| [[File:Edmund Herring by William Dargie.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Lieutenant General]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n| Later Chief Justice of Australia. Received {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}} in 1949.\n|\n* [[South West Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Kokoda Track campaign]]\n* [[Landing at Nadzab]]\n* [[Battle of Buna\u2013Gona]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commander of Australian forces in the [[Kokoda Track campaign]].\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Leslie Morshead]]\n| [[File:Morshead (AWM 009517).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Lieutenant General]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Became General Manager of the [[Orient Steam Navigation Company]].\n|\n* [[Western Desert Campaign]]\n* [[Siege of Tobruk]]\n* [[Battle of Sio]]\n* [[South West Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Borneo campaign]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Led the famous Australia defence against [[Erwin Rommel|Rommel's]] in [[siege of Tobruk]]. Commander at the [[El Alamein|Battle of El Alamein]]. Australia forces took 22 percent of the casualties there. After learning the art of [[jungle warfare]], was a very competent commander of operations against the Japanese in [[New Guinea]].\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#3c4645; color:white;\" rowspan=\"2\"|'''Air Force'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Charles Burnett (RAF officer)|Charles Burnett]]\n| [[File:Air Chf Mshl Sir Charles Burnett.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Air Chief Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n| RAF officer loaned to Australia and served as [[Chief of Air Force (Australia)|Chief of the Air Staff]] from 1940 to 1942. Oversaw a 20-fold increase in the size of the RAAF which supported the [[Empire Air Training Scheme]]. Returned to Great Britain in 1942 and while suffering poor health worked in the RAF's cadet organisation, the [[Air Training Corps]]. Died of a coronary thrombosis months before the end of the War.\n|\n* [[Chief of Air Force (Australia)|Chief of Air Force]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Fighter ace during the First World War. Deputy Commander of RAF in the Middle East.\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#3c4645; color:white;\" rowspan=\"2\"|'''Air Force'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Peter Roy Maxwell Drummond]]\n| [[File:004353Drummond1.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Air Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Died in an air crash at sea, 1945.\n|\n* [[Air officer commanding|Air Officer Commanding-in-Chief Middle East]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Fighter ace during the First World War. Deputy Commander of RAF in the Middle East.\n|- style=\"background:white;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:navy; color:white;\" rowspan=\"2\"|'''Navy'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[John Gregory Crace]]\n| [[File:John Gregory Crace.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Vice Admiral]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n| Commanded [[Chatham Dockyard]] in Britain.\n|\n* [[Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Battle of the Coral Sea]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|Commanded the Australian navy in the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]]. Commander of the [[ANZAC Squadron|Allied Naval Squadron]], [[ANZAC Force]].\n|}\n\n==== New Zealand ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000; color:white;\"| Armed Force\n! colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! Highest Rank<br><small>held during World War II</small>\n! Highest Award\n! Fate\n! Theatres / Battles\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" rowspan=\"2\"|'''Army'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bernard Freyberg, 1st Baron Freyberg]]\n| [[File:Bernard Freyberg.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Lieutenant General]]\n| [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]], [[Distinguished Service Order]]<br>Holder of the [[Victoria Cross]] plus three other [[Distinguished Service Order]]s (World War I)\n| Returned to New Zealand and later became Governor-General\n|\n* [[Battle of Greece]]\n* [[Battle of Thermopylae (1941)]]\n* [[Battle of Crete]]\n* [[North African Campaign]]\n* [[Tunisia Campaign]]\n* [[Italian Campaign (World War II)]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| A veteran of the [[Mexican Revolution]] and [[Victoria Cross]] recipient during the First World War. First soldier on beach for the [[Battle of Gallipoli]] during the First World War and the youngest general in the British Army during the First World War.<ref>[http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/publications/pointer/journals/2008/v34n3/personality_profile.html.print.html?Status=1 Youngest General WW1] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015162016/http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/publications/pointer/journals/2008/v34n3/personality_profile.html.print.html?Status=1 |date=15 October 2013 }}</ref> He liked to be in the thick of action\u2014Churchill called him \"the Salamander\" due to his love of fire. Involved in the disastrous defeat in the [[Battle of Greece]]. Again defeated as the Allied Commander in the [[Battle of Crete]] after Churchill failed to provide [[enigma machine|enigma]] intelligence. Very successful as a commander in various campaigns in the [[North African Campaign]], including the [[Second Battle of El Alamein|Battle of El Alamein]]. Defeated again at the [[Battle of Cassino]] as a Corps Commander (this is nonsense-the Germans lost at Cassino-how could Freyberg be defeated?). Relieved [[Padua]] and [[Venice]], and was first to enter [[Trieste]] in the race for Trieste, and successfully confronted [[Josip Broz Tito]]'s [[Partisans (Yugoslavia)|Partisans]] there. By the end of World War II, Freyberg had spent ten and a half long years fighting the Germans (1940-1945 plus 1916-1918 equals 7 years-he fought the Turks in 1915).<ref>[http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2-2Ita-c12-1.html Freyberg - Archives from Italy]</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| style=\"background:#000001; color:white;\" rowspan=\"6\"|'''Air Force'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Arthur Coningham (RAF officer)|Arthur Coningham]]\n| [[File:Arthur Coningham (RAF officer).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Air Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Missing in [[Bermuda Triangle]].\n|\n* [[North African Campaign]]\n* [[Western Desert Campaign]]\n* [[First Battle of El Alamein]]\n* [[Second Battle of El Alamein]]\n* [[Operation Torch]]\n* [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian Campaign]]\n* [[North-West Europe Campaign]]\n* [[Invasion of Normandy|Normandy campaign]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|A high scoring air ace in World War I. Air force Commander working with famous Major General [[George Patton]] during [[Operation Torch]]. Commander of tactical Air Forces for [[Operation Husky]] and [[D-Day]].\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Keith Park]]\n| [[File:Sir Keith Park.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Air Chief Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n| Returned to New Zealand.\n|\n* [[Battle of France]]\n* [[Battle of Britain]]\n* [[Siege of Malta (World War II)|Battle of Malta]]\n* [[Pacific Theatre of Operations]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| A veteran of World War I and air ace. Served under [[Hugh Dowding]] and commanded the defense of London during the Luftwaffe attacks. Dowding and Park are credited with winning the [[Battle of Britain]]. Led the defense of [[Malta]].\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Roderick Carr]]\n| [[File:Air Mshl Sir Roderick Carr.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Air Marshal]]\n| [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n| Air Officer Commanding Indian Air Force, 1946\n|\n* [[Battle of Britain]]\n* [[RAF Bomber Command]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\"| Served in the [[Royal Naval Air Service]] during the First World War. Commander of [[Northern Ireland]] [[RAF]]. Bomber Command Commander 4 Group. Deputy Chief of Staff (Air), [[SHAEF]].\n|}\n\n==== Poland ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000; color:white;\"| Armed Force\n! colspan=\"2\"|Name\n! Highest Rank\n! Highest Award\n! Fate\n! Theatres / Battles\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"12\" style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" |'''Army'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Edward Rydz-\u015amig\u0142y]]\n| [[File:Marshal Rydz-Smigly LOC hec 27123.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshal of Poland]]\n| [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]\n| Suffered heart attack before he could participate in the Polish resistance.\n|\n* [[Invasion of Poland]]\n* [[Camp of Fighting Poland|Fighting Poland Movement]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" | Was commander-in-chief of Poland during its invasion by German and Russian troops.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]]\n| [[File:Wladyslaw Sikorski 2.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]\n| Died in plane crash July 1943.\n|\n* [[Polish Army in France (1939\u201340)|Polish Armed Forces in the West]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" | Served as Commander-in-Chief of the Polish government in exile, and formed the [[Polish Armed Forces]].<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Anders]]\n| [[File:Wladyslaw Anders.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]\n| Became [[Inspector-General]] of the [[Polish contribution to World War II#Polish Armed Forces in the West|Polish Armed Forces in Exile]].\n|\n* [[Anders' Army|Polish Armed Forces in the East]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\