colspan=\"7\" |Chief of staff of the Army, 1931\u20131940\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Hisaichi Terauchi]]\n| [[File:Hisaichi Terauchi 2.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Field Marshal]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Died in a prisoner of war camp in Malaya June 1946.\n|\n* [[South West Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Kokoda Track campaign]]\n* [[South-East Asian theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Battle of Mount Song]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Son of former PM [[Terauchi Masatake]], became the senior officer of the Imperial Japanese after the coup of 1936. Was at one time considered as Tojo successor after the latter's resignation.\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Shunroku Hata]]\n| [[File:Shunroku Hata.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Field Marshal]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Sentenced to imprisonment.\n|\n* [[Second Sino-Japanese War]]\n* [[Battle of Taierzhuang]]\n* [[Battle of Wuhan]]\n* [[Zhejiang-Jiangxi Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Henan-Hunan-Guangxi]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Commanded the [[Second General Army (Japan)|Second General Army]], based in Hiroshima from 1944 to 1945 in preparation for the anticipated [[Operation Downfall|Allied invasion of the Japanese home islands]].\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Tomoyuki Yamashita]]\n| [[File:Yamashita Tomoyuki.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Executed at 1946.\n|\n* [[South-East Asian theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Japanese invasion of Thailand]]\n* [[Malayan Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Kampar]]\n* [[Battle of Singapore]]\n* [[Invasion of Sumatra (1942)|Invasion of Sumatra]]\n* [[Battle of Leyte]]\n* [[Battle of Ormoc Bay]]\n* [[Invasion of Lingayen Gulf]]\n* [[Battle of Luzon]]\n* [[Battle of Bessang Pass]]\n* [[Raid at Cabanatuan]]\n* [[Battle of Maguindanao]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Forced the surrender of the allies in the [[Battle of Singapore]]. Defender of the Philippines against MacArthur. an American military tribunal in Manila tried General Yamashita for war crimes relating to the [[Manila Massacre]] and many atrocities in the Philippines and Singapore against civilians and prisoners of war, such as the [[Sook Ching massacre]], and sentenced him to death. This controversial case has become a precedent regarding the command responsibility for war crimes and is known as the Yamashita Standard.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Iwane Matsui]]\n| [[File:Iwane Matsui.jpg|100px]]\n| [[General]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Retired 1938, executed in 1948.\n|\n* [[Second Sino-Japanese War]]\n* [[Battle of Shanghai]]\n* [[Battle of Nanjing]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Arrested by the American occupation authorities after the surrender of Japan, Matsui was charged with war crimes in connection with the actions of the Japanese army in China also known as The [[Nanking Massacre]]. In 1948, the International Military Tribunal for the Far East (IMTFE) found him guilty of class B and C war crimes, and he was hanged that December at Sugamo Prison, alongside six others, including Hideki Tojo. He was 70 at the time of his death.\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"14\" style=\"background:navy; color:white;\" |'''Navy'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Osami Nagano]]\n| [[File:Osami Nagano.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Gensui (Imperial Japanese Navy)|Fleet Admiral]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Died of a heart attack in 1947.\n|\n* [[Supreme War Council (Japan)|Supreme War Council]]\n* [[Pacific War]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Chief of the Navy General Staff, 1941-1944.\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Prince Fushimi Hiroyasu]]\n| [[File:Prince Fushimi Hiroyasu.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Gensui (Imperial Japanese Navy)|Fleet Admiral]]\n| [[Order of the Chrysanthemum]]\n| Died in 1946.\n|\n* [[Supreme War Council (Japan)|Supreme War Council]]\n* [[Pacific War]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Chief of staff of the Navy, 1932-1941.\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Isoroku Yamamoto]]\n| [[File:Yamamoto-Isoroku.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Gensui (Imperial Japanese Navy)|Fleet Admiral]]\n| [[Order of the Chrysanthemum]]\n| The plane carrying him was shot down in 1943.\n|\n* [[Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Attack on Pearl Harbor]]\n* [[Battle of Midway]]\n* [[Solomon Islands campaign]]\n* [[Invasion of Tulagi (May 1942)]]\n* [[Guadalcanal Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Savo Island]]\n* [[Battle of the Eastern Solomons]]\n* [[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands]]\n* [[Naval Battle of Guadalcanal]]\n* [[Battle of Rennell Island]]\n* [[Operation Ke]]\n* [[Operation I-Go]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" |Commander of the Dec. 7, 1941 [[Attack on Pearl Harbor]], Hawaii. Commander-in-Chief of the Imperial Japanese Navy 1939-1943. Isoroku Yamamoto, was killed on Bougainville Island when his transport bomber aircraft was shot down by United States Army Air Forces fighter aircraft operating from Kukum Field on Guadalcanal.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Mineichi Koga]]\n| [[File:Koga Mineichi 3.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Gensui (Imperial Japanese Navy)|Fleet Admiral]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Killed in plane crash 1944.\n|\n* [[Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n* [[Battle of Hong Kong]]\n* [[Bombing of Rabaul (November 1943)]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" |Commander-in-Chief of the Imperial Japanese Navy 1943-1944.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Soemu Toyoda]]\n| [[File:Toyoda Soemu.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Admiral]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Died in 1957 at the age of 73.\n|\n* [[Supreme War Council (Japan)|Supreme War Council]]\n* [[Pacific War]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" |Commander-in-Chief of the Imperial Japanese Navy 1944-1945, Chief of staff of the Navy 1945.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Ch\u016bichi Nagumo]]\n| [[File:Chuichi Nagumo.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Admiral]]\n| [[Order of the Rising Sun]]\n| Committed suicide in 1944 during the battle of Saipan.\n|\n* [[Attack on Pearl Harbor]]\n* [[Indian Ocean raid]]\n* [[Bombing of Darwin, February 19, 1942|Bombing of Darwin]]\n* [[Battle of Midway]]\n* [[Battle of the Eastern Solomons]]\n* [[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands]]\n* [[Battle of Saipan]]\n|- style=\"background:#edf1f1;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Torpedo specialist and commander of the [[Carrier Striking Task Force]] that attacked Pearl Harbor. Successful raids at Darwin and the Indian Ocean were reversed at the Battle of Midway. Although he had tactical victories in the Guadalcanal campaigns, his battle strength was severely depleted, and was switched to the defence of the Mariana Islands.<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Jisabur\u014d Ozawa]]\n| [[File:Ozawa11.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Vice Admiral]]\n| [[Order of the Sacred Treasure]]\n| Died in 1966.\n|\n* [[Invasion of Sumatra (1942)]]\n* [[Battle of Palembang]]\n* [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]]\n* [[Battle of Leyte Gulf]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" | Replaced Toyoda in 1945 to become commander-in-chief of the [[Japanese Combined Fleet]]<ref name=\"TOCTWW2\" />\n|}\n\n[[Masaharu Homma]]\n\n==== Hungary ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#000; color:white;\" | Armed Force\n! colspan=\"2\" |Name\n! Highest Rank\n! Highest Award\n! Fate\n! Theatres / Battles\n|- style=\"background:#fff;vertical-align: top;\"\n| rowspan=\"14\" style=\"background:#78866b; color:white;\" |'''Army'''\n| rowspa